PHP Plamodel Method
A new external OS structure for building web applications with parts, settings, and composition.

## 1. Overview
The PHP Plamodel Method is an external‑structure OS concept that treats programs as parts, changes behavior through settings, and builds features through composition.
It does not depend on internal logic or hidden frameworks.
Everything is controlled by a simple, unified external grammar.

This repository defines the external specification only.
Internal logic, internal reasoning, and internal implementation details remain private to each creator.

## 2. Core Philosophy (External Only)
The method is based on three external principles:

1. Part‑ization
Break logic into small, reusable parts.

2. Setting‑ization
Control behavior using settings instead of rewriting code.

3. Composition
Combine parts to build features, similar to assembling a plastic model.

These principles allow anyone to build applications without touching internal logic.

## 3. Three‑Layer Structure
The system is organized into three external layers:

1. parts / flow
External components

Define what the application does

Fully replaceable and shareable

2. model.php
Receives values from parts

Passes them to the core

No internal logic is exposed

3. core.php
The internal engine (not included here)

Completely separated from external grammar

Each creator owns their own core

This separation ensures safety, portability, and clear ownership.

## 4. External Grammar (10 Actions)
The method uses a fixed external grammar of 10 actions.
These actions define how parts communicate with the model and core.

Examples include:

get

filter

sort

render

validate

store

(Full list is defined in the external specification.)

This grammar is stable and does not depend on internal logic.

## 5. Market Structure
Because parts follow a unified external grammar:

Parts can be shared, sold, or exchanged

Each part’s internal logic belongs to its creator

Only the external interface is standardized

This enables a new ecosystem similar to a “parts marketplace.”

